04342nam a22006375i 9780271091136DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710911367 a10.1515/97802710911362doi  a(DE-B1597)586169  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDG618.4b.V48 2012 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a944/.5850280922231 aVester, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRenaissance Dynasticism and Apanage Politics :bJacques de Savoie-Nemours, 1531-1585 /cMatthew Vester. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps, Portraits, and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Dynasties and Political Culture in Renaissance Europe -- t2. Violence and Honor: Jacques de Savoie in the Service of Henry II, 1546-1558 -- t3. Honor, Sexuality, and Marriage in the Françoise de Rohan Scandal -- t4. Treaties, Tragedy, Tumults, and the First War of Religion, 1558-1563 -- t5. The Apanage of the Genevois and Its New Duchess, 1564-1566 -- t6. Renaissance Warrior and Courtier, ca. 1566-1570 -- t7. Dynastic Prestige, A Self-Regulating Mechanism: Dynastic Relations among Members of the House of Savoy -- t8. Local Political Autonomy in the Apanage of the Genevois -- t9. Conflicts of the Late 1570s -- t10. Piedmontese Postlude -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most brilliant courtiers and military leaders in Renaissance France, Jacques de Savoie, duke of Nemours, was head of the cadet branch of the house of Savoy, a dynasty that had ruled over a collection of lands in the Western Alps since the eleventh century. Jacques' cousin Emanuel Filibert, duke of Savoy and ruler of the Sabaudian lands, fought against Jacques, and each expanded their influence at the other's expense, while also benefitting from the other's position. This study examines the complex and rich relationship of the noble cousins that spanned the battlefields, bedchambers, courts, and backrooms of taverns from Paris to Turin to the frontiers between the Genevois and Geneva. Each prince played key roles in sixteenth-century European politics due to their individual and dynastic identities. Jacques' apanage of the Genevois was a virtual state-within-a-state, the institutional expression of a simultaneously competitive and cooperative relationship between two branches of a sovereign house. Here Matthew Vester provides a new picture of the nobility and of the European political landscape that moves beyond old views and taps into the unspoken cultural rules governing dynastic relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271091136zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271091136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271091136.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK